{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17653905","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17653905"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:49:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:49:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18592"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18592","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18592"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.08,0,0.84,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11324"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79555"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11324","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11324"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18592"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64859"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10388"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26238"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26245"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27199"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79555","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79555"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EWernicke\u0027s area is located in the posterior third of the left hemisphere of the brain.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes its primary function?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Storage of vocabulary","Production of fluent speech","Control of tongue movements","Comprehension of written and spoken language","Processing of emotional content"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComprehension of written and spoken language\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary function of Wernicke\u0027s area, which is located in the posterior portion of the superior temporal gyrus. This region is crucial for understanding both written text and spoken words. Damage to this area results in Wernicke\u0027s aphasia (receptive aphasia), where patients can speak fluently but have difficulty understanding language.\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProduction of fluent speech\u003C/strong\u003E - This is primarily the role of Broca\u0027s area in the frontal lobe\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EControl of tongue movements\u003C/strong\u003E - This is managed by the primary motor cortex and associated motor areas\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProcessing of emotional content\u003C/strong\u003E - This is primarily handled by the limbic system and amygdala\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStorage of vocabulary\u003C/strong\u003E - While Wernicke\u0027s area is involved in language comprehension, vocabulary storage involves distributed networks throughout the temporal lobe\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWernicke\u0027s area works in conjunction with Broca\u0027s area via the arcuate fasciculus to create a complete language network that allows both comprehension and production of speech.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Wernicke\u0027s area is located in the posterior section of the superior temporal gyrus and is crucial for language comprehension.","Damage to Wernicke\u0027s area results in receptive aphasia, where patients can speak fluently but have impaired understanding.","Wernicke\u0027s area connects to Broca\u0027s area via the arcuate fasciculus to integrate language comprehension and production."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64859"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18592"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64859","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64859"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-15T07:57:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-15T07:58:06+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11324"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79555"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4930"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Nervous System","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17